  <BuyingGuideSection>
    <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying Guide: How to Choose a Scale That You’ll Actually Use</h2>
    <p>Start with your brew priority. Espresso-first users should filter options by response speed and footprint before looking at extras. Pour-over-first users should prioritize display readability and timer ergonomics. Hybrid users should target a compact model that still feels comfortable under drippers and servers.</p>
    <p>Second, decide whether you want “workflow depth” or “workflow simplicity.” If you track recipes and compare coffees often, app-connected options can provide real value. If your goal is fast, repeatable daily brewing, a clean non-app model often delivers better value and fewer distractions.</p>
    <p>Third, buy for physical compatibility, not marketing claims. Measure your espresso tray area and confirm the scale dimensions before checkout. This one step prevents the most common purchase regret in this category.</p>
    <p>Fourth, treat the scale as one part of a system. Consistency gains are strongest when you combine scale-based dosing with stable grind settings and repeatable brew ratios. If your grinder is inconsistent, even the best scale cannot fully rescue cup quality.</p>
    <p>Finally, build a baseline recipe and log short notes for one week. Keep dose, yield, and time fixed, then adjust one variable at a time. That process turns your scale from a gadget into a reliable decision tool for better coffee.</p>
